 during the period 1954–98. Three forms of intervention are discussed: competitive, cooperative, and co-optative. None of them contributed to the emergence of what is called a hurting balance of power -- a necessary, if not sufficient, condition for democratic compromise and maturation; none has the capacity to allow democratization to emerge and mature in the immediate term. While competitive intervention perpetuated hegemonic instability, cooperative and co-optative intervention seemed to lead the country in the direction of illiberal democracy, in which greater hegemonic stability exists and may persist for some time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060668340uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981230592340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789812305923423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789812305923.jpg  a978-3-11-060668-3  ISEAS eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK